At 100 °C in dioxane, cy-cloheptadienone derivative 5 was produced in 21% yield along with a trace of rearranged cycloheptadienone 6 (Scheme II). Longer reflux times led to formation of greater amounts of cyclo-heptadienone 6 at the expense of 5. Cycloheptadienone 5 was converted to 6 after 2 h at 140 °C; the mechanism presumably involves consecutive 1,5-hydride shifts.4 In contrast to previous results obtained with alkylcarbene-tungsten complexes and alk-ynes,5 the cycloaddition reaction was never complete at 100 eC.
